.docname {The Toolchain: mise & moon}
.include {docs}

CrowdVision is a polyglot monorepo â€” TypeScript services, a Python AI agent, a Rust contracts service, plus shared JS tooling. To keep that manageable, the developer experience is built on **three cooperating layers**, each with a single, well-defined responsibility:

.var {headers}
   - Layer
   - Owns
   - Config

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - **`just`**
      - The human-facing CLI. Every workflow is a `just <recipe>`; it also drives the things the layers below don't (Docker, Kubernetes, docs).
      - `Justfile`
    - - **`mise`**
      - **Tool versions.** The single source of truth for which Node / Python / Rust / uv / moon you run, on every OS.
      - `mise.toml`
    - - **`moon`**
      - **Per-project task orchestration** â€” build, test, lint, audit, deps â€” with caching and affected-detection.
      - `moon/`

Underneath, two small Node scripts (`scripts/install.mjs`, `scripts/clean.mjs`) handle dependency installation, because that one job doesn't fit moon's model. Everything else is `mise` + `moon`.

.mermaid
    flowchart TD
      dev([You]) --> just["just &lt;recipe&gt;"]
      just --> mise["mise exec â€” injects pinned tools onto PATH"]
      mise --> moon["moon â€” task graph Â· caching Â· affected"]
      mise --> scripts["scripts/install.mjs Â· clean.mjs"]
      moon --> tasks["build Â· test Â· lint Â· audit Â· deps"]
      scripts --> query["moon query projects"]
      cfgA["mise.toml"] -->|versions| mise
      cfgB["moon/workspace.yml"] -->|package list| moon
      cfgB -->|package list| query

---

## âš™ď¸Ź Why this exists

Before this setup, tools were resolved from whatever happened to be on your `PATH`. That is fragile: a globally-installed Node from `nvm` or a Rust from `rustup` would silently shadow the versions the project expects, and a tool with **no** global fallback (notably `uv`) would simply fail:

```text
'uv' is not recognized as an internal or external command
```

The fix is the principle that runs through this whole page: **never trust the ambient `PATH`; resolve every tool through `mise`, and let one config file be the source of truth for each concern.**

---

## đź“Ś mise â€” the toolchain manager

[mise](https://mise.jdx.dev/) pins every language runtime and CLI to an exact version, per project, cross-platform. The pins live in **`.mise.toml`** at the repo root:

```toml
[tools]
node = "24"
python = "3.12"
rust = "stable"
"ubi:moonrepo/moon" = "latest"
uv = "latest"
```

Run `mise install` once after cloning and every one of those tools is fetched at the pinned version into mise's own store â€” independent of anything else on your machine.

### How tools actually get resolved

There are two ways mise can put those tools on your `PATH`, and the project is designed to work **with or without** the first:

.var {headers}
   - Mechanism
   - When
   - How

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - **Shell activation**
      - Interactive work in your own terminal.
      - `mise activate pwsh \| Out-String \| Invoke-Expression` (PowerShell), or `mise activate bash`/`zsh`. Add it to your shell profile to make it permanent. Tools are then on `PATH` directly â€” `node`, `uv`, `moon` all just work.
    - - **`mise exec --`**
      - Scripts, CI, the `Justfile` â€” anywhere that must work *without* assuming activation.
      - `mise exec -- <command>` resolves the tool from `mise.toml` and runs it, injecting the pinned tools onto `PATH` for that command **and every child process it spawns**.

.box type:{note}
    You do **not** need to activate mise for `just` to work. Every recipe that calls a managed tool already wraps it in `mise exec --`, so a fresh clone with only `just` + `mise` installed works immediately. Activation is purely a convenience for running tools by hand.

### `mise exec` is everywhere in the Justfile

Every `Justfile` recipe that invokes a **mise-managed** tool (`node`, `npm`, `uv`, `cargo`, `moon`) is prefixed with `mise exec --`. Tools mise does *not* manage (`docker`, `k3d`, `kubectl`) are called directly. For example:

```bash
# Justfile recipes wrap every mise-managed tool in `mise exec --`:
install:    mise install  &&  mise exec -- node scripts/install.mjs
test:       mise exec -- moon run :test
logs:       docker compose -f compose.runtime.yml logs -f   # NOT mise-managed
```

### `withMise()` â€” the same rule inside the scripts

The Node scripts that `just` launches (`install`, `clean`) spawn tools of their own. They route those through the same gate via a tiny helper, `scripts/lib/mise.mjs`:

```js
// Wrap a command so its tool resolves from mise â€” unless we can already see a
// mise-provided environment (the Justfile launches scripts under `mise exec`,
// which exports __MISE_DIFF), in which case we don't wrap it twice.
export function withMise(cmd) {
  const inside = process.env.__MISE_DIFF || process.env.MISE_SHELL;
  return inside ? cmd : `mise exec -- ${cmd}`;
}
```

This means a script works **both** when launched via `just` (already under `mise exec`) **and** when run directly as `node scripts/install.mjs` on a shell that never activated mise.

.box type:{warning}
    If any tool ever reports *"command not found"* (classically `uv`), it means something bypassed mise. Run it through `mise exec -- <tool>`, or activate mise in your shell. The tool is installed â€” it just isn't on the un-activated `PATH`.

---

## đźŚ™ moon â€” the task orchestrator

[moon](https://moonrepo.dev) runs the per-project tasks â€” `build`, `test`, `lint`, `lint-fix`, `audit`, `deps` â€” across the whole monorepo, with two capabilities the old hand-rolled scripts never had:

*   **Caching** â€” task results are hashed by their inputs. If nothing a task depends on changed, the cached result is replayed in milliseconds instead of re-running.
*   **Affected detection** â€” `--affected` runs a task only for the projects touched on your current branch.

### The project registry â€” one source of truth

Every package is registered once in **`.moon/workspace.yml`**. This is *the* list of packages in the repo â€” nothing else hand-maintains it:

```yaml
projects:
  client: "client"
  auth-service: "server/auth-service"
  twin-service: "server/twin-service"
  # â€¦ the other services â€¦
  contracts-service: "server/contracts-service"
  sensor-simulator: "simulators/sensor-simulator"
  # Support packages: deps-only, no build/test/lint
  tooling: "tooling"
  eslint-config: "tooling/eslint-config"
  tests: "server/tests"
```

### Tasks are defined once per language

Rather than repeat the same `test`/`lint`/`build` config in twelve `moon.yml` files, the pipeline is defined **once per language** in `.moon/tasks/*.yml`, and each file is scoped with `inheritedBy` so it only applies to projects of that language:

.var {headers}
   - File
   - Applies to
   - Tasks it defines

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `moon/tasks/typescript.yml`
      - `language: typescript`
      - `build` Â· `test` Â· `lint` Â· `lint-fix` Â· `deps` Â· `audit`
    - - `moon/tasks/python.yml`
      - `language: python`
      - `test` Â· `lint` Â· `lint-fix` Â· `deps` Â· `audit`
    - - `moon/tasks/rust.yml`
      - `language: rust`
      - `build` Â· `test` Â· `lint` Â· `deps` Â· `audit`
    - - `moon/tasks/javascript.yml`
      - `language: javascript`
      - `deps` only â€” for the support packages

A language file looks like this â€” note the `inheritedBy` block, which is what scopes it:

```yaml
# moon/tasks/typescript.yml
inheritedBy:
  language: 'typescript'
tasks:
  test:
    command: 'npm test'
    inputs: ['src/**/*', '__tests__/**/*', 'package.json']
  audit:
    command: 'npm audit --audit-level=high --omit=dev'
    options: { cache: false }
  # â€¦ build, lint, lint-fix, deps â€¦
```

.box type:{note}
    **Why `npm test` for the Python service?** `agent-service`'s `package.json` proxies `npm test` â†’ `uv run pytest` and `npm run lint` â†’ `uv run ruff â€¦ && pyright`. This gives moon one uniform task interface across languages while the real work still runs through `uv`.

### Each project's `moon.yml` is tiny

Because the pipeline is inherited, a standard service's entire moon config is two lines:

```yaml
language: 'typescript'
# build / test / lint / lint-fix / deps / audit inherited from moon/tasks/typescript.yml
```

Projects only declare what genuinely differs:

.var {headers}
   - Project
   - Override

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `client`
      - Uses Vite/Vitest: overrides `build` inputs, `test` â†’ `npm run test:unit`, and a TS eslint config â€” with `mergeArgs: replace` / `mergeInputs: replace` so the overrides *replace* the inherited values instead of appending.
    - - `sensor-simulator`
      - Has no unit-test suite wired into CI, so it **excludes** the inherited `test` task via `workspace.inheritedTasks.exclude`.
    - - `tooling`, `eslint-config`, `tests`
      - Tagged `language: 'javascript'` so they inherit only `deps` â€” they have no build/test/lint pipeline of their own. (`server/tests`' jest suite is integration-only and runs via `just test-integration`, never as a moon `:test`.)

### Inspecting the graph

These read-only commands are the fastest way to understand or debug the setup â€” they show resolved config without running anything:

```bash
# Read-only â€” these print resolved config without running anything:
mise exec -- moon task auth-service:test   # one task: command, inputs, inheritance
mise exec -- moon query projects           # every project moon knows (id + language)
mise exec -- moon query tasks              # which projects expose each task
```

---

## đź”— How the layers cooperate â€” single source of truth

The payoff of this design is that **each fact lives in exactly one place**:

.var {headers}
   - Question
   - Answered by

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - "Which version of Node / uv / Rust?"
      - `mise.toml`
    - - "Which packages exist in the repo?"
      - `moon/workspace.yml`
    - - "How is a TypeScript project tested/linted/audited?"
      - `moon/tasks/typescript.yml`

Crucially, **`install` and `clean` derive their package list from moon** rather than keeping a parallel hand-written list. `scripts/lib/workspaces.mjs` shells out to `moon query projects` and buckets the result by language:

```js
const { projects } = JSON.parse(execSync(withMise('moon query projects')));
```

So `just install` installs exactly the packages moon knows about â€” no drift possible.

.box type:{note}
    `install` and `clean` stay as scripts (not moon tasks) on purpose: `npm ci` wipes and reinstalls `node_modules`, which isn't a cacheable artifact, and the only "proper" way to make moon manage installs is to enable moon's own toolchain â€” which would download a second Node and conflict with mise being the single source of truth. So moon owns build/test/lint/audit/deps; the scripts own install/clean; mise owns versions.

---

## âž• Adding a new service or package

Thanks to the single registry, onboarding a package is a **one-place change**:

1. **Register it** in `.moon/workspace.yml` under `projects:`.
2. **Add a minimal `moon.yml`** in the package with just its `language:` (and any genuine task overrides).
3. That's it. It now flows automatically into `:build` / `:test` / `:lint` / `:audit` / `:deps` **and** into `just install` / `just clean-install` (because both derive from `moon query projects`).

.box type:{warning}
    Pick the `language` deliberately. `typescript` / `python` / `rust` inherit the **full** build/test/lint pipeline â€” only use them for packages that actually have those scripts. Use `javascript` for support packages that need dependency installs but have no build/test/lint (like `tooling`).

---

## đź§° Command reference

### mise

.var {headers}
   - Command
   - Purpose

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `mise install`
      - Install every tool pinned in `mise.toml` (run once after cloning; also runs as the first step of `just install`).
    - - `mise exec -- <cmd>`
      - Run a command with the pinned tools on `PATH` (and inherited by its children).
    - - `mise activate <shell>`
      - Put the pinned tools on `PATH` for your interactive shell (optional convenience).
    - - `mise ls`
      - Show installed tools and their resolved versions.

### moon (via `mise exec --`)

.var {headers}
   - Command
   - Purpose

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `moon run :test`
      - Run the `test` task for every project that defines it (caching applies).
    - - `moon run :lint --affected`
      - Run `lint` only for projects changed on the current branch.
    - - `moon run :audit` / `:deps`
      - Security audit / lockfile-sync check across all projects.
    - - `moon run <project>:<task>`
      - Run one task for one project, e.g. `moon run twin-service:lint`.
    - - `moon task <project>:<task>`
      - Print the **resolved** task config without running it.
    - - `moon query projects` / `query tasks`
      - Dump the project graph / task map as JSON.

### just

Most day-to-day work goes through `just`, which wraps the moon/mise commands for you. See the [Running the Application](running.qd) page for the full recipe table; the toolchain-relevant ones are:

.var {headers}
   - Recipe
   - Delegates to

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `just install`
      - `mise install` + `node scripts/install.mjs` (list from `moon query projects`)
    - - `just clean-install`
      - Wipe + regenerate all lockfiles (cross-OS), then reinstall
    - - `just test` / `just test-affected`
      - `moon run :test` (`--affected`)
    - - `just lint` / `just lint-affected` / `just lint-fix`
      - `moon run :lint` (`--affected`) / `:lint-fix`
    - - `just audit`
      - `moon run :audit`
    - - `just deps-check`
      - `moon run :deps`

---

## đź“š Building this documentation

The guides you are reading are written in [Quarkdown](https://github.com/iamgio/quarkdown) (`.qd`) under `documentation/`, and compiled to the static `landing-page/` site (the same output GitHub Pages publishes). Three `just` recipes cover it (Quarkdown CLI + a JDK 17+ must be on your `PATH`):

.var {headers}
   - Recipe
   - What it does

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `just docs`
      - Compile both guides to `landing-page/user` and `landing-page/dev` (mirrors CI).
    - - `just docs-preview dir=developer`
      - Quarkdown's own live-reloading server for a single guide while editing (`dir=user` by default).
    - - `just docs-serve`
      - Build both guides, then live-serve the **whole** `landing-page/` site (index + guides + API docs) at `http://localhost:8080` with auto-reload.

.box type:{note}
    Editing workflow: leave `just docs-serve` running, edit `.qd` files, then run `just docs` in another terminal to rebuild â€” the server reloads the browser automatically.

---

## đź©ş Troubleshooting

.var {headers}
   - Symptom
   - Cause & fix

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `'uv' is not recognized` / `command not found`
      - A tool was called outside mise. Use `mise exec -- <tool>`, or activate mise in your shell. The tool is installed; it just isn't on the un-activated `PATH`.
    - - `link.exe not found` during `cargo` (Windows)
      - Rust compiles to lint/test and needs the MSVC linker. Install **Visual Studio Build Tools** with the *"Desktop development with C++"* workload. (Not a toolchain bug â€” every native Rust dev on Windows needs this; macOS needs `xcode-select --install`, Linux needs `build-essential`.)
    - - `just test`/`just lint` re-runs everything every time
      - Expected on the first run. The second run replays from moon's cache (near-instant). Use `--affected` to scope to changed projects.
    - - A new service isn't tested/installed
      - It isn't registered in `moon/workspace.yml`, or its `moon.yml` is missing / has the wrong `language`. Verify with `mise exec -- moon query projects`.
